Chairman and Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of the Nigerian Diaspora Commission (NIDCOM), Mrs. Abike Dabiri-Erewa has revealed that Nigerians in the Diaspora remitted about $25 billion, excluding informal remittances into the nationâ€™s coffers in 2019.  Fielding questions from journalists after a closed door meeting with President Muhammadu Buhari at the presidential villa in Abuja, Mrs Dabiri-Erewa said that the Commission is hoping to create a wholistic database to capture all informal remittances and planning to create a Diaspora Trust Fund to engage and ensure Nigerians abroad contribute to the nation's development.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the NIDCOM boss briefed the President on her 2019 activities, short, medium and longterm plans of the commission as well as lamenting inadequate funding of the commmission.  Speaking on Mr President's directive on Diasporans welfare and for a database to capture all Nigerians abroad, she also disclosed that a Diaspora Policy for Nigeria has been sent to the Federal Executive Council for ratification in the New year.  She however reiterated that the commission is engaging the National Assembly to amend Electoral laws to see to the possibility of Nigerians abroad voting in future elections.